His landscapes were often dramatic, with swirling skies and exaggerated features, such as cypress trees or wheat fields. His still lifes were full of vibrant colors and textures, with simple objects like flowers or fruit taking on a lively personality. His portraits were often of people he knew, with exaggerated features and vivid expressions that revealed their personality. Composition: Van Goghs compositions were often asymmetrical, with objects placed off-center or at unusual angles. His use of perspective was unconventional, with objects appearing to be flattened or elongated.
